.TH NET-PING 1 "2026-04-29" "net-mgr" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
net-ping \- manual fping producer; reset RTT baselines
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B net-ping
.I IP
.RI [ IP
.IR ... ]
.br
.B net-ping
.B \-\-auto
.br
.B net-ping
.B \-\-reset
.RI [ IP
.IR ... ]
.br
.B net-ping
.B \-\-reset
.B \-\-all
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B net-ping
fpings the given IPs and pushes
.B kind=ping
observations to the daemon, updating each address's
.B last_rtt_ms
and
.BR min_rtt_ms .
The same data is gathered automatically by
.B net-discover \-\-presence
on a periodic schedule; this tool exists for ad-hoc probing and for clearing
stale baselines.
.PP
.B \-\-reset
issues a
.B TRIGGER reset-rtt
to the daemon (handled in-process, no fork) which clears
.B min_rtt_ms
and
.BR last_rtt_ms .
Useful when a host's recorded minimum was set during an unusual condition
(e.g. you tested with the iface in promisc mode) and is no longer
representative.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-auto
Snapshot every known v4 address and ping them all.
.TP
.B \-\-reset
Clear RTT baselines instead of pinging. Combine with IPs, or with
.B \-\-all
to clear everything.
.TP
.B \-\-all
With
.BR \-\-reset ,
clear every row.
.TP
\fB\-\-listen\fR \fIHOST:PORT\fR
Override the manager address.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Ping a few hosts and update their RTTs:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-ping 192.168.15.1 192.168.15.42
.fi
.RE
.PP
Ping everything we know about:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-ping --auto
.fi
.RE
.PP
Reset baseline for one IP after testing:
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-ping --reset 192.168.15.42
.fi
.RE
.PP
Reset every baseline (e.g. after a network reconfig):
.RS 4
.nf
.B net-ping --reset --all
.fi
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR net-watch (1),
.BR net-discover (1),
.BR net-mgr (7)
